n"}]}}]}],"annotations":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-10623/canvas/1/page/p1","type":"AnnotationPage","items":[{"id":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-10623/canvas/1/b3cdfbe9-84e7-4044-b062-f17f1e07179c","type":"Annotation","motivation":"commenting","body":[{"created":"2026-06-30T18:58:40.078Z","creator":"Tallulah Stallvik","purpose":"commenting","type":"TextualBody","format":"text/html","value":"<p>According to Vicky Krieps, while there were extensive rehearsals for the film, Daniel Day-Lewis did come to her the day before shooting the asparagus scene in order to ensure that she (or perhaps both of them) were well prepared for this tense moment in <em>Phantom Thread</em> (Los Angeles Times, “<a target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noreferrer noopener\" class=\"Hyperlink SCXW224063542 BCX0\" href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=myq3eX0o1kc\"><u>Phantom Thread Vicky Krieps On The Tense Dinner Scenes</u></a>”). They shot the scene twice, and the moments when Alma says what she thinks of Reynolds are improvised by Krieps: “It just came.”</p>"}],"target":{"type":"SpecificResource","source":"https://digitalscholarship.brynmawr.edu/pta/phan/phan-10623/canvas/1","selector":{"type":"FragmentSelector","conformsTo":"http://www.w3.org/TR/media-frags/","value":"xywh=pixel:28.61657872009829,29.754423058547488,289.4425675675676,236.00788288288288"}}}]}]}]}